05392nam a22006015i 9780822394075DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223940757 a10.1515/97808223940752doi  a(DE-B1597)553745  a(OCoLC)1202623894  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHM753b.S87 2011 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a305.4208922200aStrange Affinities :bThe Gender and Sexual Politics of Comparative Racialization /cRoderick A. Ferguson, Grace Kyungwon Hong. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (380 p.) :b10 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerverse Modernities: A Series Edited by Jack Halberstam and Lisa Lowe00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction Grace Kyungwon Hong Roderick A. Ferguson -- tOne. Racialized Hauntings of the Devalued Dead -- tTwo. I = Another: Digital Identity Politics -- tThree. Reading Tehran in Lolita Making Racialized and Gendered Difference Work for Neoliberal Multiculturalism -- tFour. The Lateral Moves of African American Studies in a Period of Migration -- tFive. Volumes of Transnational Vengeance Fixing Race and Feminism on the Way to Kill Bill -- tSix. Time for Rights? Loving, Gay Marriage, and the Limits of Comparative Legal Justice -- tSeven. Romance with a Message W. E. B. Du Bois's Dark Princess and the Problem of the Color Line -- tEight. ''In the Middle'' The Miseducation of a Refugee -- tNine. Deconstructing the Rhetoric of Mestizaje through the Chinese Presence in Mexico -- tTen. Fun with Death and Dismemberment Irony, Farce, and the Limits of Nationalism in Oscar Zeta Acosta's The Revolt of the Cockroach People and Ana Castillo's So Far from God -- tEleven. Becoming Chingón/a A Gendered and Racialized Critique of the Global Economy -- tTwelve. Black Orientalism Nineteenth-Century Narratives of Race and U.S. Citizenship -- tThirteen. ''A Deep Sense of No Longer Belonging'' Ambiguous Sites of Empire in Ana Lydia Vega's Miss Florence's Trunk -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRepresenting some of the most exciting work in critical ethnic studies, the essays in this collection examine the production of racialized, gendered, and sexualized difference, and the possibilities for progressive coalitions, or the "strange affinities," afforded by nuanced comparative analyses of racial formations. The nationalist and identity-based concepts of race underlying the mid-twentieth-century movements for decolonization and social change are not adequate to the tasks of critiquing the racial configurations generated by neocolonialism and contesting its inequities. Contemporary regimes of power produce racialized, gendered, and sexualized violence and labor exploitation, and they render subjects redundant and disposable by creating new, nominally nonracialized categories of privilege and stigma. The editors of Strange Affinities contend that the greatest potential for developing much-needed alternative comparative methods lies in women of color feminism, and the related intellectual tradition that Roderick A. Ferguson has called queer of color critique. Exemplified by the work of Audre Lorde, Cherríe Moraga, Barbara Smith, and the Combahee River Collective, these critiques do not presume homogeneity across racial or national groups. Instead, they offer powerful relational analyses of the racialized, gendered, and sexualized valuation and devaluation of human life.ContributorsVictor BascaraLisa Marie CachoM. Bianet CastellanosMartha Chew SánchezRoderick A. FergusonGrace Kyungwon HongHelen H. JunKara KeelingSanda Mayzaw LwinJodi MelamedChandan ReddyRuby C. TapiaCynthia Tolentino  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF tit